body: This seems like a reasonable enhancement to me, however I do wonder what the autofixing behavior should be for array destructuring when the index > 0. i.e. should it autofix `const foo = bar[2];` to `const [,, foo] = bar;`?

I think it probably shouldn’t autofix in that case - since it’s iterable destructuring, not array destructuring, and there’s no guarantee that an object with a 2 property is either an array or iterable.

What about nested destructuring cases, in addition to the cases above?

My thinking is, this would be a pretty significant implementation and maintenance burden, unless we only cover very simple cases and just don't bother with the rest. I'm currently mildly opposed to this for that reason, but could be persuaded.
I would be happy if it only auto-fixed the simple case, like `let x = a.x;` => `let {x} = a;`.

issue.title: Update: add fixer for `prefer-destructuring` (fixes #11151)
